The diagonal matrix σAB has the principal angles between the subspaces spanned by αA and αB as its diagonal entries. Since those subspaces are the same, σAB=I for any two Laplacians. We then calculate UA=αAOA and UB=αBOB. Since σAB is constant, UA=UB, and U is constant for all points on the geodesic; α and O are not constant, though. Furthermore, we can use the same U matrix for any Laplacian of a given dynamic graph without affecting our calculations, because the span of U is constant. We calculate R=UTLU for LA and LB. The geodesic from LA at t=0 to LB at t=1 is then 
